         \### Variables set automatically\n\
         \\n\
         \Pandoc sets these variables automatically in response to [options] or\n\
         \document contents; users can also modify them. These vary depending\n\
         \on the output format, and include the following:\n\
         \\n\
         \`body`\n\
         \:   body of document\n\
         \\n\
         \`date-meta`\n\
         \:   the `date` variable converted to ISO 8601 YYYY-MM-DD,\n\
         \    included in all HTML based formats (dzslides, epub,\n\
         \    html, html4, html5, revealjs, s5, slideous, slidy).\n\
         \    The recognized formats for `date` are: `mm/dd/yyyy`,\n\
         \    `mm/dd/yy`, `yyyy-mm-dd` (ISO 8601), `dd MM yyyy`\n\
         \    (e.g. either `02 Apr 2018` or `02 April 2018`),\n\
         \    `MM dd, yyyy` (e.g. `Apr. 02, 2018` or `April 02, 2018),\n\
         \    `yyyy[mm[dd]]` (e.g. `20180402, `201804` or `2018`).\n\
         \\n\
         \`header-includes`\n\
         \:   contents specified by `-H/--include-in-header` (may have multiple\n\
         \    values)\n\
         \\n\
         \`include-before`\n\
         \:   contents specified by `-B/--include-before-body` (may have\n\
         \    multiple values)\n\
         \\n\
         \`include-after`\n\
         \:   contents specified by `-A/--include-after-body` (may have\n\
         \    multiple values)\n\
         \\n\
         \`meta-json`\n\
         \:   JSON representation of all of the document's metadata. Field\n\
         \    values are transformed to the selected output format.\n\
         \\n\
         \`numbersections`\n\
         \:   non-null value if `-N/--number-sections` was specified\n\
         \\n\
         \`sourcefile`, `outputfile`\n\
         \:   source and destination filenames, as given on the command line.\n\
         \    `sourcefile` can also be a list if input comes from multiple files,\n\
         \    or empty if input is from stdin. You can use the following snippet in\n\
         \    your template to distinguish them:\n\
         \\n\
         \        $if(sourcefile)$\n\
         \        $for(sourcefile)$\n\
         \        $sourcefile$\n\
         \        $endfor$\n\
         \        $else$\n\
         \        (stdin)\n\
         \        $endif$\n\
         \\n\
         \    Similarly, `outputfile` can be `-` if output goes to the terminal.\n\
         \\n\
         \    If you need absolute paths, use e.g. `$curdir$/$sourcefile$`.\n\
         \\n\
